Professional Profile

A Chartered professional, that specialises in leveraging technology to deliver large, complex construction projects. Experienced in full RIBA lifecycle, using a forward-thinking approach to empower teams, overcome challenges, and consistently deliver projects that exceed expectations in safety, quality, sustainability, profitability and social benefits.


Industry Experience

	PROJECT MANAGER 								   APR 22 – PRESENT
Middlebeck Urban Extension, Newark (Urban and Civic) - £200m
Lead Project Manager delivering a 694-acre urban extension. The project involves delivering 3,000 homes, over 6km of nationally significant highway infrastructure, three major structures, 10-pylon power diversions, 2m+ sq. ft. of industrial space, a primary school, and a local district centre in flood zone 3.

Responsibilities:
Acting as the client under CDM ensuring Health and Safety from inception to completion. Oversee the master cost plan and programme. Undertake cash flow forecasts, contingency planning, and change control. Prepare, analyse and administer construction and consultancy contracts, appointments, warranties and agreements. Manage stakeholder relationships with local and national authorities to prevent delays and ensure project continuity. Manage infrastructure design, planning, delivery and adoption processes.

Key Achievements:
•	Innovation in Reporting: Designed and implemented an automated health and safety reporting tool, AI invoicing system and automated contract creation and management which has been adopted company-wide, saving time, spend on external consultants and increases consistency across 12 strategic land sites.
•	Delivered Major Infrastructure: Managed the design, procurement, planning approval and construction of 4km of strategic road network, 2 bridges (100m and 30m), strategic sustainable urban drainage, 1 million m3 of earthworks, 12 utility diversions and 2 new installs to power development. 


	ASSISTANT PROJECT MANAGER 					                  MAY 21 to MAR 22
DCL178 Lapworth Canal Bridge Replacement, Lapworth (Story Contracting) - £7m
Client-facing role overseeing the design and delivery of a replacement of a rail bridge over a canal. Contract type was an NEC3 (Option 3 – Target Cost) contract. The project involved lifting operations with three cranes, pontoon supported temporary works for abutment supports and railway line reconstruction.

Responsibilities:
Undertook delegated CRE-C duties to manage the design development for temporary and permanent works. Managed all supply chain appointments, defining scopes of work and supporting commercial reporting. Led all progress meetings with the client, councils, and supply chain. Administered compensation events, early warnings, and change requests in line with NEC3 contract. Developed and maintained project programmes, collaborating with construction managers, site teams, and planners to keep the project on schedule.

Key Achievements:
•	Cost and Efficiency Improvements: Conducted a contract review recovering £150k in additional project funding. Identified and implemented design amendments for temporary works saving £30k.
•	Successful Project Delivery: Planned and delivered a complex canal rail bridge replacement within a 5-day blockade. This included an unplanned train and crane activity over a 6-mile stretch. Earned a Network Rail Safety Award and an Office of Road and Rail commendation which was featured on their LinkedIn page.
•	Innovative Problem-Solving: Eliminated the need for contaminated material removal (Japanese Knotweed) which reduced costs and environmental impact. Introduced a document control system to enhance collaboration across multidisciplinary teams.








	SECTION ENGINEER								     DEC 20 to APR 21
Stocks Overbridge Replacement, Evesham (Graham Construction) - £10m
Road bridge over rail replacement with a precast structure. The project involved lifting operations, bridge installation, earthworks and road construction.  

Responsibilities:
Managed all site activities and personnel against approved method statements and specifications. Led client progress meetings. Managed technical development of graduate engineers. Undertook subcontractor appointments. Coordinated material procurement, plant, and labour to meet programme requirements. Involved in monthly subcontractor and client application for payments.

Key Achievements:
•	Efficient Project Delivery: Successfully led civil engineering activities to complete a bridge replacement over three 30-hour blockades which finished ahead of schedule.
•	Safety and Quality Excellence: Consistently achieved above 90% in site safety audits with a peak score of 98%.
•	Cost Savings and Innovation: Designed and implemented changes to access stairs resulting a £15k cost saving.


	SECTION ENGINEER						     		    JUN 20 to NOV 20  
CP6 Kelston Park, Bath (Graham Construction) - £3.5m
Stabilisation of a 1km railway embankment. The project included earthworks, king post piled wall installation, and temporary diversion of utilities.

Responsibilities:
Supervised junior engineers, checking their work for accuracy. Acted as Temporary Works Coordinator, overseeing the safe implementation of temporary structures, particularly over live utilities. Produced health, safety, quality and environmental documentation. Managed material procurement process.



	SITE ENGINEER					    			    JUN 19 to MAY 20
Crossrail Train Stations, London - (Graham Construction) - £46m
Construction of the new Acton Mainline Station and upgrade works at Ealing Broadway Station. The project involved piling, structural steel, curtain walling and deep drainage along with mechanical, electrical and interior fitout.

Responsibilities:
Setting out and supervising site activities. Maintenance of health, safety, quality, and environmental documentation. Coordination of site activities to mitigate risks and keep the project on schedule.




